{"TopicId":128440,"ForumId":44,"TopicTitle":"Some questions regarding orbits","CreatedByName":"Martian Music","CreatedById":154849,"CreatedDateTime":"2015-12-22T16:09:47Z","PageNum":1,"Articles":[{"CreatedByName":"Martian Music","CreatedById":154849,"CreatedDateTime":"2015-12-22T16:09:47Z","Content":"\n\u003Cp\u003E\nWell my main question is the views from orbit. So I recently found out that the ISS is at a 400km orbit (lol) but when you look at pictures taken from the ISS and compare them to KSP, you need to be in a 70km orbit (in KSP) to get the same view. So what am I missing here? LEO apparently reaches out to 500km orbits, how is that a\u00A0\u0022low\u0022 orbit?\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nThanks in advance. (ISS is visible in my sky in 5 mins, as \u003Ca contenteditable=\u0022false\u0022 data-ipshover=\u0022\u0022 data-ipshover-target=\u0022http://forum.kerbalspaceprogram.com/index.php?/profile/149920-sanic/\u0026amp;do=hovercard\u0022 data-mentionid=\u0022149920\u0022 href=\u0022https://forum.kerbalspaceprogram.com/index.php?/profile/149920-sanic/\u0022\u003E@Sanic\u003C/a\u003E\u00A0says.. gotta go fast!)\u00A0\n\u003C/p\u003E\n"},{"CreatedByName":"Shpaget","CreatedById":45577,"CreatedDateTime":"2015-12-22T16:14:12Z","Content":"\n\u003Cp\u003E\nKerbin is a lot smaller than Earth.\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\n\u003Cimg class=\u0022ipsImage\u0022 src=\u0022http://i49.tinypic.com/2qwmn1k.png\u0022 alt=\u00222qwmn1k.png\u0022\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cspan class=\u0022ipsType_reset ipsType_medium ipsType_light\u0022 data-excludequote=\u0022\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cstrong\u003EEdited \u003Ctime datetime=\u00222015-12-22T16:14:57Z\u0022 title=\u002212/22/2015 04:14  PM\u0022 data-short=\u00228 yr\u0022\u003EDecember 22, 2015\u003C/time\u003E by Shpaget\u003C/strong\u003E\n\u003C/span\u003E\n"},{"CreatedByName":"swjr-swis","CreatedById":152460,"CreatedDateTime":"2015-12-22T16:15:50Z","Content":"\n\u003Cp\u003E\nKerbin is a lot smaller than Earth (check the radius in tracking center), so to see the same curvature you need to be in a much closer orbit.\n\u003C/p\u003E\n"},{"CreatedByName":"Martian Music","CreatedById":154849,"CreatedDateTime":"2015-12-22T16:22:24Z","Content":"\n\u003Cp\u003E\nOhh I never looked at Kerbin\u0027s diameter lol. Thanks guys, makes sense now ;p\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nP.S: I missed the ISS -.- my android app is supposed to ring when there\u0027s a sighting. It rang at 6:10 PM while the ISS\u00A0was visible from 6:00 PM to 6:02\u00A0PM. Gonna uninstall\u00A0the app I guess ;p\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cspan class=\u0022ipsType_reset ipsType_medium ipsType_light\u0022 data-excludequote=\u0022\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cstrong\u003EEdited \u003Ctime datetime=\u00222015-12-22T16:23:43Z\u0022 title=\u002212/22/2015 04:23  PM\u0022 data-short=\u00228 yr\u0022\u003EDecember 22, 2015\u003C/time\u003E by Martian Music\u003C/strong\u003E\n\u003C/span\u003E\n"},{"CreatedByName":"Red Iron Crown","CreatedById":12858,"CreatedDateTime":"2015-12-22T16:43:54Z","Content":"\n\u003Cblockquote class=\u0022ipsQuote\u0022 data-ipsquote=\u0022\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentapp=\u0022forums\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentclass=\u0022forums_Topic\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentcommentid=\u00222332754\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentid=\u0022128440\u0022 data-ipsquote-contenttype=\u0022forums\u0022 data-ipsquote-timestamp=\u00221450800852\u0022 data-ipsquote-userid=\u002245577\u0022 data-ipsquote-username=\u0022Shpaget\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cdiv class=\u0022ipsQuote_citation\u0022\u003E\n29 minutes ago, Shpaget said:\n\u003C/div\u003E\n\u003Cdiv class=\u0022ipsQuote_contents\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nKerbin is a lot smaller than Earth.\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\n\u003Cimg alt=\u00222qwmn1k.png\u0022 class=\u0022ipsImage\u0022 src=\u0022http://i49.tinypic.com/2qwmn1k.png\u0022\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003C/div\u003E\n\u003C/blockquote\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nOdd\u00A0for such a well constructed image to get Kerbin\u0027s radius wrong, it\u0027s actually 600km.\n\u003C/p\u003E\n"},{"CreatedByName":"Shpaget","CreatedById":45577,"CreatedDateTime":"2015-12-22T16:51:36Z","Content":"\n\u003Cp\u003E\nGood eye!\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nLet\u0027s all\u00A0blame \u003Ca contenteditable=\u0022false\u0022 data-ipshover=\u0022\u0022 data-ipshover-target=\u0022http://forum.kerbalspaceprogram.com/index.php?/profile/4115-hayoo/\u0026amp;do=hovercard\u0022 data-mentionid=\u00224115\u0022 href=\u0022https://forum.kerbalspaceprogram.com/index.php?/profile/4115-hayoo/\u0022\u003E@Hayoo\u003C/a\u003E\u00A0for it.\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cspan class=\u0022ipsType_reset ipsType_medium ipsType_light\u0022 data-excludequote=\u0022\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cstrong\u003EEdited \u003Ctime datetime=\u00222015-12-22T16:52:10Z\u0022 title=\u002212/22/2015 04:52  PM\u0022 data-short=\u00228 yr\u0022\u003EDecember 22, 2015\u003C/time\u003E by Shpaget\u003C/strong\u003E\n\u003C/span\u003E\n"},{"CreatedByName":"Martian Music","CreatedById":154849,"CreatedDateTime":"2015-12-22T16:54:04Z","Content":"\n\u003Cp\u003E\nSo Jool is smaller than Earth? Cool ;p\n\u003C/p\u003E\n"},{"CreatedByName":"Frida Space","CreatedById":60943,"CreatedDateTime":"2015-12-22T17:16:27Z","Content":"\n\u003Cblockquote class=\u0022ipsQuote\u0022 data-ipsquote=\u0022\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentapp=\u0022forums\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentclass=\u0022forums_Topic\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentcommentid=\u00222332768\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentid=\u0022128440\u0022 data-ipsquote-contenttype=\u0022forums\u0022 data-ipsquote-timestamp=\u00221450801344\u0022 data-ipsquote-userid=\u0022154849\u0022 data-ipsquote-username=\u0022Martian Music\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cdiv class=\u0022ipsQuote_citation\u0022\u003E\n1 hour ago, Martian Music said:\n\u003C/div\u003E\n\u003Cdiv class=\u0022ipsQuote_contents\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nOhh I never looked at Kerbin\u0027s diameter lol.\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003C/div\u003E\n\u003C/blockquote\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nThat\u0027s why it only takes 3300 m/s of Delta V to get in LKO compared to the roughly 9500 m/s needed for LEO \u003Cimg alt=\u0022:)\u0022 data-emoticon=\u0022true\u0022 src=\u0022//kerbal-forum-uploads.s3.us-west-2.amazonaws.com/emoticons/default_k_smiley.gif\u0022 title=\u0022:)\u0022\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\n"},{"CreatedByName":"Martian Music","CreatedById":154849,"CreatedDateTime":"2015-12-22T19:38:03Z","Content":"\n\u003Cp\u003E\nAnd yet I still sometimes fail to orbit. Hahaha epic!\n\u003C/p\u003E\n"},{"CreatedByName":"swjr-swis","CreatedById":152460,"CreatedDateTime":"2015-12-22T20:04:53Z","Content":"\n\u003Cp\u003E\nThat\u0027s because it\u0027s not the size of the boat that matters, it\u0027s the depth of the gravity well.\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nOr something.\n\u003C/p\u003E\n"},{"CreatedByName":"Bill Phil","CreatedById":127797,"CreatedDateTime":"2015-12-22T20:21:28Z","Content":"\n\u003Cp\u003E\nThere\u0027s something called angular size. It\u0027s actually really cool how it works. It depends on the linear size of the object and the distance to\u00A0the object.\u00A0\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nLet\u0027s compare 500 to 6000(rounded...) It\u0027s 1/12. Adding it make 6500 km. If\u00A0those were concentric circles the outer one would be the orbit in question. It hugs the earth. Quite closely.\n\u003C/p\u003E\n"},{"CreatedByName":"Scotius","CreatedById":57622,"CreatedDateTime":"2015-12-22T21:49:00Z","Content":"\n\u003Cp\u003E\n400 km orbit IS low \u003Cimg alt=\u0022:)\u0022 data-emoticon=\u0022true\u0022 src=\u0022//kerbal-forum-uploads.s3.us-west-2.amazonaws.com/emoticons/default_k_smiley.gif\u0022 title=\u0022:)\u0022\u003E ISS needs regular boosts from visiting ships (or her own propulsion system) to stay in orbit, because it still experiences significant amount of atmospheric drag. For the same reason, during station\u0027s night solar panels are rotated to make the station more aerodynamic \u003Cimg alt=\u0022:)\u0022 data-emoticon=\u0022true\u0022 src=\u0022//kerbal-forum-uploads.s3.us-west-2.amazonaws.com/emoticons/default_k_smiley.gif\u0022 title=\u0022:)\u0022\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\n"},{"CreatedByName":"SuperFastJellyfish","CreatedById":57985,"CreatedDateTime":"2015-12-22T22:51:59Z","Content":"\n\u003Cp\u003E\nI always like visualizations.\u00A0 Here\u0027s a graph from \u003Ca href=\u0022http://www.heavens-above.com/IssHeight.aspx\u0022 rel=\u0022external nofollow\u0022\u003Ehere\u003C/a\u003E:\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\n\u003Cimg alt=\u0022OrbitHeightPlot.aspx?Width=800\u0026amp;Height=60\u0022 class=\u0022ipsImage\u0022 src=\u0022http://www.heavens-above.com/OrbitHeightPlot.aspx?Width=800\u0026amp;Height=600\u0026amp;satid=25544\u0026amp;cul=en\u0022\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cspan class=\u0022ipsType_reset ipsType_medium ipsType_light\u0022 data-excludequote=\u0022\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cstrong\u003EEdited \u003Ctime datetime=\u00222015-12-22T22:56:36Z\u0022 title=\u002212/22/2015 10:56  PM\u0022 data-short=\u00228 yr\u0022\u003EDecember 22, 2015\u003C/time\u003E by SuperFastJellyfish\u003C/strong\u003E\n\u003C/span\u003E\n"},{"CreatedByName":"KerbonautInTraining","CreatedById":145373,"CreatedDateTime":"2015-12-23T03:09:13Z","Content":"\n\u003Cblockquote class=\u0022ipsQuote\u0022 data-ipsquote=\u0022\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentapp=\u0022forums\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentclass=\u0022forums_Topic\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentcommentid=\u00222333218\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentid=\u0022128440\u0022 data-ipsquote-contenttype=\u0022forums\u0022 data-ipsquote-timestamp=\u00221450820940\u0022 data-ipsquote-userid=\u002257622\u0022 data-ipsquote-username=\u0022Scotius\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cdiv class=\u0022ipsQuote_citation\u0022\u003E\n5 hours ago, Scotius said:\n\u003C/div\u003E\n\u003Cdiv class=\u0022ipsQuote_contents\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\n400 km orbit IS low \u003Cimg alt=\u0022:)\u0022 data-emoticon=\u0022true\u0022 src=\u0022//kerbal-forum-uploads.s3.us-west-2.amazonaws.com/emoticons/default_k_smiley.gif\u0022 title=\u0022:)\u0022\u003E ISS needs regular boosts from visiting ships (or her own propulsion system) to stay in orbit, because it still experiences significant amount of atmospheric drag. For the same reason, during station\u0027s night solar panels are rotated to make the station more aerodynamic \u003Cimg alt=\u0022:)\u0022 data-emoticon=\u0022true\u0022 src=\u0022//kerbal-forum-uploads.s3.us-west-2.amazonaws.com/emoticons/default_k_smiley.gif\u0022 title=\u0022:)\u0022\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003C/div\u003E\n\u003C/blockquote\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nI read somewhere that what you\u0027re describing is called the \u0022Night Glider\u0022 mode or something. It\u0027s only done when propulsion isn\u0027t going to be in abundance, as it puts extra wear on certain components,\n\u003C/p\u003E\n"},{"CreatedByName":"Martian Music","CreatedById":154849,"CreatedDateTime":"2015-12-23T08:21:06Z","Content":"\n\u003Cp\u003E\nYeah I\u0027ve heard of the boosts, that also made me wonder how a \u0022high\u0022 400km orbit would experience that much drag but yeah I was unaware of the size comparison ;p thanks everyone.\n\u003C/p\u003E\n"},{"CreatedByName":"tomf","CreatedById":57809,"CreatedDateTime":"2015-12-24T13:32:44Z","Content":"\n\u003Cp\u003E\nAlso Kerbin\u0027s atmosphere dissapears abruptly at just below 70km whereas Earth\u0027s atmosphere just gets very gradually more tenuous.\n\u003C/p\u003E\n"}]}